explanation:
Why each symbol is needed to decide if any operations in OS_BinSemGetInfo are dead code:

- OS_CHECK_POINTER
  - This macro can cause an early exit, logging, or other side-effects when bin_prop is NULL. To know whether the memset/strncpy/assignments afterwards are ever executed (or redundant) we must know exactly what OS_CHECK_POINTER expands to and whether it returns, aborts, or only reports an error.

- OS_ObjectIdGetById
  - Determines whether the branch that fills bin_prop (the body under if (return_code == OS_SUCCESS)) executes at all. Its behavior and side-effects (including whether it modifies token) are required to determine whether subsequent operations are reachable and meaningful.

- OS_SUCCESS
  - The constant/value used to test the return of OS_ObjectIdGetById. Needed to interpret the branch condition and whether the following code is executed.

- LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE and OS_LOCK_MODE_GLOBAL
  - The arguments passed into OS_ObjectIdGetById; their semantics may affect whether the call succeeds or has side-effects. Knowing them helps determine if the call can be optimized away safely or if it has required effects (e.g., locking) that make the call non-dead.

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET
  - Macro or accessor used to map token -> record. Its semantics determine whether reading record->name_entry and record->creator is meaningful or redundant, and whether that operation has side-effects (e.g., validation). Needed to decide if the strncpy/assignment are dead.

- OS_global_bin_sem_table
  - The table passed to OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; its layout and initialization determine what record points to and whether reading record fields is meaningful.

- OS_common_record_t
  - Structure type of record. Must know fields (name_entry, creator) and whether accessing them is required or has side-effects; needed to see if copying name_entry into bin_prop is necessary or redundant.

- OS_bin_sem_prop_t
  - Structure type of bin_prop (layout and sizes of name and creator fields). Required to determine the effect of the initial memset, the strncpy bounds, and whether later calls (OS_BinSemGetInfo_Impl) overwrite the same fields (which would make earlier writes dead).

- strncpy / memset (implicitly)
  - Although standard, their semantics (memset zeroing, strncpy partial copy and NUL behavior) are the operations under question; their known behavior is used to reason about whether those writes change observable program state or are overwritten later.

- OS_BinSemGetInfo_Impl
  - This implementation call may itself populate the same fields of bin_prop (or perform other side-effects). To decide if the prior memset, strncpy, and direct assignment to bin_prop->creator are dead (redundant) we must know what OS_BinSemGetInfo_Impl writes/does.

- OS_ObjectIdRelease
  - Releasing the token may be required for correctness (resource/transaction release). If OS_BinSemGetInfo_Impl already releases the token, this release could be redundant (dead). Conversely, if it is required and unique, removing it would change behavior. So its semantics are necessary.

- OS_printf
  - Frequently used by OS_CHECK_POINTER or error-path macros to report failures. If OS_CHECK_POINTER logs via OS_printf, that affects whether removing OS_CHECK_POINTER (or other error handling) changes observable behavior. Include to determine logging side-effects.

In summary: to establish whether the zeroing/copy/assignment/release calls in OS_BinSemGetInfo are dead, we must know (a) whether the function can early-exit (OS_CHECK_POINTER), (b) whether the branch body executes (OS_ObjectIdGetById + OS_SUCCESS + related args), (c) what values are read from the object table (OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET, OS_global_bin_sem_table, OS_common_record_t), (d) the exact layout and fields of bin_prop (OS_bin_sem_prop_t) and whether they are later overwritten by OS_BinSemGetInfo_Impl, and (e) whether the token release is required or redundant (OS_ObjectIdRelease).
